<subSubSection lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1626,2013]" lastBlockId="36.[151,1437,150,537]" lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1806,1832]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Description</emphasis>
. Male. Body length, 
<quantity box="[566,632,1807,1833]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[640,704,1807,1833]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Head</emphasis>
. Frons brown, sparsely setulose, with well-defined median furrow. Flagellomere 1 light brown, conical very elongate. Arista apical, about one-third flagellomere 1 length. Palpus light brown. Gena with two to three setae. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[563,652,1879,1905]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Thorax</emphasis>
. Scutum, scutellum, and pleural regions brown; anepisternum dorsally setulose. Foreleg yellowish brown; mid and hind leg light brown. Foretibia with two dorsal setae, anterodorsal row of strong setulae, posteroventral uneven row of strong setae and three apical ventral strong setae. Foremetatarsus with anterior excavation bearing orange microtrichia, anteroapical setulose process, group of setae at excavation base and strong seta at anteroapical process base (
<figureCitation box="[700,788,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="18.[151,250,921,945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,897]" captionTargetId="figure-31@18.[151,1436,181,897]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male foremetatarsus of new species of Coniceromyia, continuation (scale bars=0.1mm). A. C. platypoda, B. C. polychaeta, C. C. puntarenensis, D. C. riccardiae, E. C. setosa, F. C. solaris, G. C. stichochaeta, H. C. strongyla, I. C. systenopoda, J. C. trilobata, K. C. xiei." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402870/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
). Foretarsomeres 2–5 short and wide. Foremetatarsus ratio 0.43. Hind femur expanded ventrally, with narrow basoventral band of tiny blunt setulae (
<figureCitation box="[1157,1237,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[183,1405,181,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-20@43.[183,1405,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 21. Hind femora of the males of Coniceromyia new species, continuation (scale bars on figures of the entire femur=0.3 mm, on figures of ventrobasal part of the femur=0.1 mm). A–B. C. niemeyeri, C–D. C. numerosa, E. C. ochyrosticha, F–G. C. parallela, H–I. C. pectinella, J–K. C. platypoda." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402902" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402902/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
J–K). Hind femur height/length ratio, 0.43. Hind tibia with one dorsal seta in basal half. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[935,1000,222,248]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1015,1118,222,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1940,1964]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,186,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-20@33.[151,1435,181,1916]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 15. Wings of the males of Coniceromyia new species, continuation. A. C. memorialis, B. C. niemeyeri, C. C. numerosa, D. C. ochyrosticha, E. C. parallela, F. C. pectinella, G. C. platypoda, H. C. polychaeta, I. C. puntarenensis, J. C. riccardiae, K. C. setosa, L. C. solaris." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402886" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402886/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 15G</figureCitation>
). Costa slightly swollen, 0.5 of the wing length; R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[397,422,277,291]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">2+3</subScript>
absent; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[541,549,277,291]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">1</subScript>
slightly concave, curved posteriorly at apex; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1099,1107,277,291]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">2</subScript>
slightly sinuous; M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1336,1344,277,291]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">1</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,277,291]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">2</subScript>
thicker than CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[343,351,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">1</subScript>
; CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[419,427,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">1</subScript>
-M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[461,469,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">2</subScript>
/M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[502,510,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">2</subScript>
-M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[544,552,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">1</subScript>
ratio 1.8; CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[719,727,313,327]" fontSize="6" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">1</subScript>
slightly sinuous. Halter white. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1076,1193,294,320]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Tergites brown, with shining pubescence. Hypopygium light brown (
<figureCitation box="[683,787,330,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,182,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-20@49.[151,1436,181,1877]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 25. Hypopygia of Coniceromyia new species in right lateral view, continuation. A. C. megalosoma, B. C. memorialis, C. C. niemeyeri, D. C. numerosa, E. C. ochyrosticha, F. C. parallela, G. C. pectinella, H. C. platypoda, I. C. polychaeta, J. C. puntarenensis, K. C. riccardiae, L. C. setosa, M. C. solaris, N. C. stichochaeta, O. C. strongyla, P. C. systenopoda, Q. C. trilobata, R. C. xiei." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4402914" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4402914/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 25H</figureCitation>
), left epandrial process with only one discernible process: a subepandrial wall extending from the hypoproct to its apex. Subepandrial wall with a group of approximately ten setulae. Margin of right lobe of hypandrium without lateral projection. Hypoproct with two setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1027,438,465]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,150,537]" box="[199,1027,438,465]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,438,464]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Distribution</emphasis>
. Known from a single locality in Pacific Coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[909,1023,439,465]" name="Colombia" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Colombia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,475,501]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Etymology</emphasis>
. Name derived from the Greek roots 
<emphasis box="[760,827,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">platys</emphasis>
(broad, wide) and 
<emphasis box="[1045,1112,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">podos</emphasis>
(foot), referring to the short and wide foretarsomeres 2–5.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
